overview: The user initiated a request to fix numerous issues within a pull
  request, emphasizing critical Vercel deployment failures. The agent
  systematically addressed a wide array of problems, starting with lint errors
  and progressing to significant security vulnerabilities, such as replacing an
  insecure 'true' cookie with HMAC-signed session tokens compatible with
  Vercel's Edge Runtime. Functional bugs like PDF NaN values, inaccurate time
  calculations, and a hardcoded user name were resolved, alongside improvements
  to number field handling and Zod schema validation for time inputs. A major
  pivot occurred when updating Next.js to version 16.1.1 to fix a critical
  security vulnerability, which subsequently introduced breaking changes in
  Prisma and ESLint configurations that required further fixes. The persistent
  Vercel deployment failures were meticulously debugged, revealing issues with
  the Prisma schema's database URL configuration and the Prisma client's eager
  initialization during Vercel's build process. The final diagnosis for the
  Vercel deployment was a missing DATABASE_URL environment variable in the
  Vercel project settings, which the agent provided instructions for the user to
  resolve externally.
